03816nam a22006975i 9781501721441DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017214417 a10.7591/97815017214412doi  a(DE-B1597)515554  a(OCoLC)1083623143  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a381/.094/09022231 aFarber, Lianna, eauthor.13aAn Anatomy of Trade in Medieval Writing :bValue, Consent, and Community /cLianna Farber. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource :b2 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. THE STORY OF TRADE -- t2. VALUE -- t3.CONSENT -- t4. COMMUNITY -- tCONCLUSION -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tNOTES -- tWORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEconomics, in our modern sense of the term, was not a discipline in the Middle Ages, although the history of economic thought is often written as though it were. Lianna Farber restores the core economic concept of trade to its medieval contexts, showing that it contains three component parts: value, consent, and community. Medieval writing about trade not only relies on these elements, it presents them as unproblematic.By addressing texts in which each element of trade is discussed directly, Farber demonstrates that this straightforward picture is falsely reassuring. In fact, these ideas were deeply contested. In the end, Farber reveals, writing about trade was not descriptive but argumentative, analyzing the act in an attempt to justify it. Such texts reveal deep intellectual uncertainties about the market society they advocated. An Anatomy of Trade in Medieval Writing benefits from Farber's close reading of literary sources, among them the poetry of Geoffrey Chaucer and Robert Henryson; theological sources, including the writing of Thomas Aquinas and Richard of Middleton; and legal sources such as the canon law on marriage formation. A provocative contribution to our understanding of medieval life and thought, this book implies a need to reconsider the genealogy of economics as a way of thinking about the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501721441423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501721441.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG